      <hedline>
        <hl1>Honor and Beautify</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peter Golkin letter concurs with September 24 editorial opposing construction of World War II Memorial on Mall in Washington, DC</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Don't Mar the Mall'' (editorial, Sept. 24):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Don't Mar the Mall'' (editorial, Sept. 24):</p>
        <p>I agree that the proposed World War II Memorial deserves a location of prime importance in the Washington area, but not one that would disrupt the inspiring continuity of the Mall.</p>
        <p>Perhaps the memorial planners should consider placing an arch of victory over New York Avenue in the Northeast section of Washington. That roadway is the primary means of entering the city from the north,  and visitors now riding along it -- many of whom will tour the Mall -- are welcomed only by a depressing string of fast-food restaurants, liquor stores and abandoned buildings.</p>
        <p>PETER GOLKIN  Arlington, Va., Sept. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
